296· Once in the Odes the ablative of agent is used without a preposition: 1, 6, 1 f. scriberis Varia . . . flsaeom'i carminis alite, ‘thou shalt be sung by Varius, that bird of Maeonian song.' With this we may compare Epist. 1, 19, 2 carmina, qaae scribun- tur aquae potoribm, ‘verses written by teetotalers,’ although most editors and grammarians regard potoribus as dative of agent. 97. The instrumental ablative is found once with a verbal noun : 3, 4, 55 truncis iaculator, ‘ he who threw trunks of trees.’
